void ROCKSDB_NAMESPACE::WritePreparedTxnDB::AdvanceMaxEvictedSeq ( const SequenceNumber & prev_max,

write_prepared_txn_db.cc 파일의 708 번째 라인에서 정의되었습니다.

709 {
710 ROCKS_LOG_DETAILS(info_log_,
711 "AdvanceMaxEvictedSeq overhead %" PRIu64 " => %" PRIu64,
712 prev_max, new_max);
713 // Declare the intention before getting snapshot from the DB. This helps a
714 // concurrent GetSnapshot to wait to catch up with future_max_evicted_seq_ if
715 // it has not already. Otherwise the new snapshot is when we ask DB for
716 // snapshots smaller than future max.
717 auto updated_future_max = prev_max;
718 while (updated_future_max < new_max &&
719 !future_max_evicted_seq_.compare_exchange_weak(
720 updated_future_max, new_max, std::memory_order_acq_rel,
721 std::memory_order_relaxed)) {
722 };

726 // With each change to max_evicted_seq_ fetch the live snapshots behind it.
727 // We use max as the version of snapshots to identify how fresh are the
728 // snapshot list. This works because the snapshots are between 0 and
729 // max, so the larger the max, the more complete they are.
730 SequenceNumber new_snapshots_version = new_max;
731 std::vector<SequenceNumber> snapshots;
732 bool update_snapshots = false;
733 if (new_snapshots_version > snapshots_version_) {
734 // This is to avoid updating the snapshots_ if it already updated
735 // with a more recent vesion by a concrrent thread

164 // remove from delayed prepared. Our reads from these two is also
165 // non-atomic. By looking into commit cache first thus we might not find the
166 // prep_seq neither in commit cache not in delayed_prepared_. To fix that i)
167 // we check if there was any delayed prepared BEFORE looking into commit
168 // cache, ii) if there was, we complete the search steps to be these: i)
169 // commit cache, ii) delayed prepared, commit cache again. In this way if
170 // the first query to commit cache missed the commit, the 2nd will catch it.

207 // happen after recovery, or it could be committed and evicted by another
208 // commit, or never committed.

211 max_evicted_seq_ub = max_evicted_seq_.load(std::memory_order_acquire);

252 snapshot_seq <= it->second);

272 // max_evicted_seq_, we have three cases: i) in delayed_prepared_, ii) in

SequenceNumber ROCKSDB_NAMESPACE::WritePreparedTxnDB::SmallestUnCommittedSeq ( )

write_prepared_txn_db.h 파일의 666 번째 라인에서 정의되었습니다.

666 {
667 // Note: We have two lists to look into, but for performance reasons they
668 // are not read atomically. Since CheckPreparedAgainstMax copies the entry
669 // to delayed_prepared_ before removing it from prepared_txns_, to ensure
670 // that a prepared entry will not go unmissed, we look into them in opposite
671 // order: first read prepared_txns_ and then delayed_prepared_.
672
673 // This must be called before calling ::top. This is because the concurrent
674 // thread would call ::RemovePrepared before updating
675 // GetLatestSequenceNumber(). Reading then in opposite order here guarantees
676 // that the ::top that we read would be lower the ::top if we had otherwise
677 // update/read them atomically.
678 auto next_prepare = db_impl_->GetLatestSequenceNumber() + 1;
679 auto min_prepare = prepared_txns_.top();
680 // Since we update the prepare_heap always from the main write queue via
681 // PreReleaseCallback, the prepared_txns_.top() indicates the smallest
682 // prepared data in 2pc transactions. For non-2pc transactions that are
683 // written in two steps, we also update prepared_txns_ at the first step
684 // (via the same mechanism) so that their uncommitted data is reflected in
685 // SmallestUnCommittedSeq.
686 if (!delayed_prepared_empty_.load()) {
687 ReadLock rl(&prepared_mutex_);
688 if (!delayed_prepared_.empty()) {
689 return *delayed_prepared_.begin();
690 }
691 }
692 bool empty = min_prepare == kMaxSequenceNumber;
693 if (empty) {
694 // Since GetLatestSequenceNumber is updated
695 // after prepared_txns_ are, the value of GetLatestSequenceNumber would
696 // reflect any uncommitted data that is not added to prepared_txns_ yet.
697 // Otherwise, if there is no concurrent txn, this value simply reflects
698 // that latest value in the memtable.
699 return next_prepare;
700 } else {
701 return std::min(min_prepare, next_prepare);
702 }
703 }

928 // We update the list concurrently with the readers.
929 // Both new and old lists are sorted and the new list is subset of the
930 // previous list plus some new items. Thus if a snapshot repeats in
931 // both new and old lists, it will appear upper in the new list. So if
932 // we simply insert the new snapshots in order, if an overwritten item
933 // is still valid in the new list is either written to the same place in
934 // the array or it is written in a higher palce before it gets
935 // overwritten by another item. This guarantess a reader that reads the
936 // list bottom-up will eventaully see a snapshot that repeats in the
937 // update, either before it gets overwritten by the writer or
938 // afterwards.
939 size_t i = 0;
940 auto it = snapshots.begin();
941 for (; it != snapshots.end() && i < SNAPSHOT_CACHE_SIZE; ++it, ++i) {
942 snapshot_cache_[i].store(*it, std::memory_order_release);
943 TEST_IDX_SYNC_POINT("WritePreparedTxnDB::UpdateSnapshots:p:", ++sync_i);
944 TEST_IDX_SYNC_POINT("WritePreparedTxnDB::UpdateSnapshots:s:", sync_i);
945 }
946#ifndef NDEBUG
947 // Release the remaining sync points since they are useless given that the
948 // reader would also use lock to access snapshots
949 for (++sync_i; sync_i <= 10; ++sync_i) {
950 TEST_IDX_SYNC_POINT("WritePreparedTxnDB::UpdateSnapshots:p:", sync_i);
951 TEST_IDX_SYNC_POINT("WritePreparedTxnDB::UpdateSnapshots:s:", sync_i);
952 }
953#endif
954 snapshots_.clear();

957 // concurrently
958 snapshots_.push_back(*it);
959 }

961 // items that are not set yet.
